'''Kars''' ({{lang-hy|<U+053F><U+0561><U+0580><U+057D>}} or <U+0542><U+0561><U+0580><U+057D> ''Ghars'',<ref name="SAE">{{cite book|contribution=<U+053F><U+0561><U+0580><U+057D> [Kars]|language=hy|last1=Arakelyan|first1=Babken|authorlink1=Babken Arakelyan|first2=Vrezh|last2=Vardanyan|first3=Hovhannes|last3=Khalpakhchyan|title=[[Armenian Soviet Encyclopedia]]|location=Yerevan|publisher=Armenian Encyclopedia|year=1979|volume=5|pp=342<U+2013>344}}</ref> {{lang-ka|<U+10E7><U+10D0><U+10E0><U+10E1><U+10D8>}} ''Kars'') is a city in northeast [[Turkey]] and the capital of [[Kars Province]].

With a population of 73,826 (in 2010), it is the largest city on the Turkish side of the border with [[Armenia]]. For a brief period of time, it served as the [[historic capitals of Armenia|capital]] of the medieval [[Bagratid Kingdom of Armenia]].<ref name="Grove Encyclopedia">{{cite book|title=The Grove Encyclopedia of Islamic Art and Architecture, Volume 3|year=2009|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-530991-1|page=[http://books.google.com/books?id=un4WcfEASZwC&pg=RA1-PA371&dq=kars+capital+armenia+928&hl=en&sa=X&ei=yeyMUpTMA7PgsASEzoGQBA&ved=0CEMQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=kars%20capital%20armenia%20928&f=false 371]|editor=Bloom, Jonathan M.; Blair, Sheila}}</ref> Its significance increased in the 19th century, when Kars was contested between the Ottoman and Russian empires, with the latter gaining control of the city as a result of the [[Russo-Turkish War (1877<U+2013>78)|1877-78 war]]. During [[World War I]], the Ottomans took control of the city in 1918, but were forced to relinquish it to the [[First Republic of Armenia]] following the [[Armistice of Mudros]]. During the [[Turkish<U+2013>Armenian War]] in late 1920, Turkish revolutionaries captured Kars for the last time. The controversial<ref>{{cite book|last=Bal|first=<U+0130>dris|title=Turkish foreign policy in post cold war era|year=2004|publisher=BrownWalker Press|location=Boca Raton, Fl.|isbn=978-1-58112-423-1|page=272|quote=Armenia's failure to recognize the Kars Agreement, along with the frequent public references to eastern Turkey as 'Western Armenia,' provides a serious irritant to Turkey.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Armenian-Turkish Protocols To Confirm Kars Treaty|url=http://asbarez.com/70572/armenian-turkish-protocols-to-confirm-kars-treaty/|accessdate=8 April 2014|newspaper=[[Asbarez]]|date=17 September 2009}}</ref> [[Treaty of Kars]] was signed in 1921 between the [[Government of the Grand National Assembly]] and the Soviet republics of Armenia, Azerbaijan and Georgia, which established the current north-eastern boundaries of Turkey.

==History==

===Etymology===
For the origin of the name "Kars", some sources claim it to be derived from the [[Georgian language|Georgian]] word <U+10D9><U+10D0><U+10E0><U+10D8> (''kari''), meaning "the gate"<ref name="trudy">{{cite book |title=International Dictionary of Historic Places: Southern Europe |last=Ring |first=Trudy |authorlink= |coauthors=Salkin, Robert M.; La Boda, Sharon |year=1996 |publisher=Taylor & Francis |isbn=1-884964-02-8|page=357|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=74JI2UlcU8AC&pg=PA357}}</ref> while other sources claim it is from the Armenian word <U+0570><U+0561><U+0580><U+057D> (''hars'') which is a [[Folk etymology|folk etymological]] word for ''bride'', or rather from <U+056F><U+0561><U+057C><U+0578><U+0582><U+0581> <U+0562><U+0565><U+0580><U+0564> (''ka<U+1E5B>uts berd''), "Ka<U+1E5B>uts Fortress".<ref>{{cite book |title=Placenames of the World |last=Room |first=Adrian |authorlink= |year=2003 |publisher=McFarland |location= |isbn=0-7864-1814-1 |page=178}}</ref> The Georgian etymology, along with a Turkish one offered by M. Fahrettin K<U+0131>rz<U+0131>o<U+011F>lu (that the name came from the "Karsak", a Turkish tribe), has been criticized by some scholars.<ref>[[Vasily Bartold|Bartold, Vasily]]-[C. J. Heywood]. "Kars." [[Encyclopedia of Islam]], 2nd ed. Leiden: E. J. Brill, 1997, vol. iv, p. 669.</ref>

===Medieval period===
[[File:Armenian Cathedral of Kars.png|thumb|260px|The 10th-century [[Cathedral of Kars|Armenian Church of the Holy Apostles]], as seen in a photo taken in the late 19th century.]]

Little is known of the early history of Kars beyond the fact that it had its own dynasty of Armenian rulers and was the capital of a region known as [[Vanand]]. As Chorzene, the town appears in Roman historiography ([[Strabo]]) as part of [[Roman Armenia|ancient Armenia]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.01.0239:book=11:chapter=14&highlight=chorzene#note-link4 | title=Geography Stabo - Book XI - Chapter XIV | accessdate=2011-05-31 | author=Strabo}}</ref> Medieval Armenian historians referred to the city by a variety of names, including "Karuts' K'aghak'" (Kars city), "Karuts' Berd", "Amrots'n Karuts'" (both meaning Kars Fortress) and "Amurn Karuts'" (Impenetrable Kars).<ref name="SAE"/> At some point in the ninth century (at least by 888) it became part of the territory of the [[Bagratuni Kingdom of Armenia|Armenian Bagratunis]]. Kars was the [[historic capitals of Armenia|capital]] of [[Bagratid Kingdom of Armenia]] between 928 and 961.<ref name="Grove Encyclopedia"/> During this period the town's cathedral, later known as the [[Cathedral of Kars|Church of the Holy Apostles]], was built.<ref>{{hy icon}} [[Varazdat Harutyunyan|Harutyunyan, Varazdat M.]] "<U+0543><U+0561><U+0580><U+057F><U+0561><U+0580><U+0561><U+057A><U+0565><U+057F><U+0578><U+0582><U+0569><U+0575><U+0578><U+0582><U+0576>" [Architecture] in ''<U+0540><U+0561><U+0575> <U+053A><U+0578><U+0572><U+0578><U+057E><U+0580><U+0564><U+056B> <U+054A><U+0561><U+057F><U+0574><U+0578><U+0582><U+0569><U+0575><U+0578><U+0582><U+0576>'' [History of the Armenian People], ed. [[Tsatur Aghayan]] et al. Yerevan: Armenian Academy of Sciences, 1976, vol. 3, pp.&nbsp;374<U+2013>375.</ref>

In 963, shortly after the Bagratuni seat was transferred to [[Ani]], Kars became the capital of a separate independent kingdom, again called Vanand. The extent of its actual independence from the Kingdom of Ani is uncertain: it was always in the possession of the relatives of the rulers of Ani, and, after Ani's capture by the [[Byzantine Empire]] in 1045, the Bagratuni title "King of Kings" held by the ruler of Ani was transferred to the ruler of Kars. In 1064, just after the capture of Ani by [[Alp Arslan]] (King of the [[Seljuk Turks]]), the Armenian king of Kars, Gagik-Abas, paid homage to the victorious Turks, so that they would not lay siege to his city. In 1065 Gagik-Abas ceded control of Kars to the Byzantine Empire, but soon after Kars was taken by the Seljuk Turks.<ref name="SAE"/>

In 1206/07 the city was captured by the [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]ns and given to the same [[Zakarid-Mxargrzeli|Zakarid]] family who ruled Ani. They retained control of Kars until the late 1230s, after which it had Turkish rulers. In 1387 the city surrendered to [[Timur]] (Tamerlane) and its fortifications were damaged. [[Anatolian beyliks]] followed until 1534, when the Ottoman army captured the city. The fortifications of the city were rebuilt by the Ottoman Sultan [[Murad III]] and were strong enough to withstand a siege by [[Nadir Shah]] of [[Persian Empire|Persia]], in 1731. It became the head of a [[sanjak]] in the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] [[Erzurum Vilayet]].

===Russian administration===
{{see also|Kars Oblast}}
[[File:Kars 1828.jpg|thumb|250px|The 1828 Russian siege of Kars (painter [[January Suchodolski]]).]]
In 1807 Kars successfully resisted an attack by the [[Russian Empire]]. After another siege in 1828 the city was surrendered on June 23, 1828 to the Russian general Count [[Ivan Paskevich]], 11,000 men becoming [[prisoners of war]]. Although it later returned to Ottoman control, the new border between the Ottoman Empire and Russia was now much closer to Kars. During the [[Crimean War]] an Ottoman garrison led by British officers including General [[William Fenwick Williams]] kept the Russians at bay during a [[Siege of Kars|protracted siege]]; but after the garrison had been devastated by cholera and food supplies had depleted, the town was [[Siege of Kars|surrendered]] to [[Nikolay Muravyov-Karsky|General Mouravieff]] in November 1855.

The fortress was again stormed by the Russians in the [[Battle of Kars]] during the [[Russo-Turkish War, 1877-78]] under generals [[Mikhail Tarielovich Loris-Melikov|Loris-Melikov]] and [[Lazarev Ivan Davidovich|Ivan Lazarev]]. Following the war, Kars was transferred to [[Russian Empire|Russia]] by the [[Treaty of San Stefano]]. Kars became the capital of the [[Kars Oblast]] (province), comprising the districts of Kars, [[Ardahan]], [[Ka<U+011F><U+0131>zman|Kaghisman]], and [[Oltu]].

From 1878 to 1881 more than 82,000 Muslims from formerly Ottoman-controlled territory migrated to the Ottoman Empire. Among those there were more than 11,000 people from the city of Kars. At the same time, many [[Armenians]] and [[Pontic Greeks]] (here usually called [[Caucasus Greeks]]) migrated to the region from the Ottoman Empire and other regions of Transcaucasia. According to the Russian census data, by 1897 [[Armenians]] formed 49.7%, [[Russians]] 26.3%, [[Caucasus Greeks]] 11.7%, [[Poles]] 5.3% and Turks 3.8%.<ref name="1897 census"/>

===World War I===
[[File:Armenians fleeing Kars.jpg|thumb|250px|Armenian civilians fleeing Kars after its capture by [[K<U+00E2>z<U+0131>m Karabekir]]'s forces.]]
In the First World War, the city was one of the main objectives of the Ottoman army during the lost [[Battle of Sarikamish]] in the [[Caucasus Campaign]]. Russia ceded Kars, [[Ardahan]] and [[Batum]] to the Ottoman Empire under the [[Treaty of Brest-Litovsk]] on March 3, 1918. However, by then Kars was under the effective control of Armenian and non-Bolshevik Russian forces. The Ottoman Empire captured Kars on April 25, 1918, but under the [[Armistice of Mudros]] (October 1918) was required to withdraw to the pre-war frontier. The Ottomans refused to relinquish Kars; its military governor instead established a government, the [[Provisional National Government of the Southwestern Caucasus]], led by Fahrettin Pirioglu, that claimed Turkish sovereignty over Kars and Turkish-speaking regions as far as Batumi and [[Gyumri|Alexandropol]] (Gyumri). Much of the region fell under the administrative control of [[Democratic Republic of Armenia|Armenia]] in January 1919 but the pro-Turkish government remained in the city until a joint operation launched by British and Armenian troops dissolved it on April 19, 1919, arresting its leaders and sending them to [[Malta exiles|Malta]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Hovannisian|first=Richard G.|authorlink=Richard G. Hovannisian|title=The Republic of Armenia, Vol. I: The First Year, 1918<U+2013>1919|publisher=University of California Press|year=1971|location=Berkeley|isbn =0-520-01984-9|pages =197<U+2013>227}}</ref> In May 1919 Kars came under the full administration of the Armenian Republic and became the capital of its Vanand province.

Skirmishes between the [[Turkish revolutionaries]] and Armenian border troops in [[Olti]] took place during the summer of 1920. In the autumn of that year four Turkish divisions under the command of General [[K<U+00E2>z<U+0131>m Karabekir]] invaded the Armenian Republic, triggering the [[Turkish-Armenian War]].<ref>{{cite book|last =Hovannisian|first=Richard G.|title=The Republic of Armenia, Vol. IV: Between Crescent and Sickle, Partition and Sovietization|publisher=University of California Press|year=1996|location=Berkeley|isbn=0-520-08804-2|pages =182ff}}</ref> Kars had been fortified to withstand a lengthy siege but, to the astonishment of all, was taken with little resistance by Turkish forces on October 30, 1920, in what some modern scholars have called one of the worst military fiascoes in Armenian history.<ref>Hovannisian. ''Republic of Armenia, Vol. IV'', pp.&nbsp;253<U+2013>261.</ref> The terms of the [[Treaty of Alexandropol]], signed by the representatives of Armenia and Turkey on December 2, 1920, forced Armenia to give back all the Ottoman territories granted to it in the [[Treaty of S<U+00E8>vres]].

After the [[Bolshevik]] advance into Armenia, the Treaty of Alexandropol was superseded by the [[Treaty of Kars]] (October 23, 1921), signed between Turkey and the [[Soviet Union]]. The treaty allowed for Soviet annexation of [[Adjara]] in exchange for Turkish control of the regions of [[Kars Province|Kars]], [[I<U+011F>d<U+0131>r Province|Igdir]], and [[Ardahan Province|Ardahan]]. The Treaty of Kars established peaceful relations between the two nations, but as early as 1939, some British diplomats noted{{citation needed|date=April 2014}} indications that the Soviet Union was not satisfied with the established border.

===Recent history===
After World War II, the Soviet Union attempted to annul the Kars treaty and regain the Kars region and the adjoining region of [[Ardahan]]. On June 7, 1945, Soviet Foreign Minister [[Vyacheslav Molotov]] told the Turkish ambassador to Moscow [[Selim Sarper]] that the regions should be returned to the [[Soviet Union]], on behalf of the Georgian and Armenian republics.  Turkey found itself in a difficult position: it wanted good relations with the Soviet Union, but at the same time they refused to give up the territories. Turkey itself was in no condition to fight a war with the Soviet Union, which had emerged as a superpower after the second world war. By the autumn of 1945, Soviet troops in the Caucasus were ordered to prepare for a possible invasion of Turkey. Prime Minister [[Winston Churchill]] objected to these territorial claims, while [[President of the United States|President]] [[Harry Truman]] initially felt that the matter should not concern other parties. With the onset of the [[Cold War]], however, the United States came to see Turkey as usefully ally against Soviet expansion and began to support it financially and militarily. By 1948 the Soviet Union dropped its clams to Kars and the other regions.<ref>Krikorian, Robert O. (2011), "Kars-Ardahan and Soviet Armenian Irredentism, 1945<U+2013>1946," in ''Armenian Kars and Ani'', ed. [[Richard G. Hovannisian]]. Costa Mesa, CA: Mazda Publishers, pp.&nbsp;393<U+2013>409.</ref>

In April 1993, Turkey closed its Kars border crossing with Armenia, in a protest against the capture of [[Kelbajar]] district of [[Azerbaijan]] by Armenian forces during the [[Nagorno-Karabakh War]].<ref name="hrw">{{Cite book|last=Panico|first = Christopher|author2=Rone, Jemera|year = 1994|title = Bloodshed in the Caucasus: Escalation of the Armed Conflict in Nagorno Karabakh|publisher = Human Rights Watch/Helsinki Watch|isbn = 1-56432-142-8|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=eDTuxhmqzSkC&pg=PA74|page=74|quote=Turkey cut all routes to Armenia in April 1993, after the Karabakh Armenian army - with alleged support from Russian and Armenian armies - seized Kelbajar province of Azerbaijan.}}</ref> Since then the land border between Armenia and Turkey has remained closed. In 2006, former Kars mayor Naif Alibeyo<U+011F>lu said that opening the border would boost the local economy and reawaken the city.<ref>"Kars battles for access to Armenia and beyond", Turkish Daily News, July 30th 2006.</ref> Despite unsuccessful attempts to establish diplomatic relations between the two countries in 2009,<ref>{{Cite news|author=Staff|title=Turkey, Armenia to Reopen Border|date=11 October 2009|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB125518039736978131.html|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20091012060227/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB125518039736978131.html|archivedate=12 October 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> there remained opposition and pressure from the local population against the re-opening of the border.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Mammadli, Sabuhi|title=Border Turks Want Door to Armenia Kept Shut|date=1 May 2009|newspaper=CRS Issue 491|publisher=Institute for War and Peace Reporting|url=http://iwpr.net/report-news/border-turks-want-door-armenia-kept-shut|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20120923224553/http://iwpr.net/report-news/border-turks-want-door-armenia-kept-shut|archivedate=23 September 2012|deadurl=no}} Note: archive not available until mid-2013.</ref> Under pressure from Azerbaijan, and the local population, including the 20% ethnic [[Azerbaijani people|Azerbaijani]] minority, the Turkish foreign minister Ahmet Davuto<U+011F>lu reiterated in 2010 and 2011 that opening the border with Armenia was out of question.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Armenia border opening out of question, says Davuto<U+011F>lu |newspaper=[[Today's Zaman]]|date=19 July 2010|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/news-216463-armenia-border-opening-out-of-question-says-davutoglu.html|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20120923225545/http://www.todayszaman.com/news-216463-armenia-border-opening-out-of-question-says-davutoglu.html|archivedate=23 September 2012|deadurl=no}} Note: archive not available until mid-2013.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.economist.com/node/17905911 |title=Two vast and ugly blocks of stone |newspaper=[[The Economist]]|date=13 January 2011}}</ref> {{As of|2014}}, the border remains closed.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Turkish, Armenian journalists want the border opened|newspaper=[[Today's Zaman]]|date=3 June 2012 |url=http://www.todayszaman.com/newsDetail_getNewsById.action?newsId=282339 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20120923230720/http://www.todayszaman.com/newsDetail_getNewsById.action?newsId=282339 |archivedate=23 September 2012|deadurl=no}} Note: archive not available until mid-2013.</ref>

==Demographics==
According to Turkey's 2011 Statistical Yearbook, the area has been depopulating because of migration to bigger cities.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Turkish Statistical Institute|year=2011|chapter=The provinces with highest out-migration according to their net migration rate|title=Turkey in Statistics 2011 (The Summary of Turkey's Statistical Yearbook 2011)|page=15|url=http://www.tuik.gov.tr/IcerikGetir.do?istab_id=5&ei=95pfUOTmCamOiAL4kIGwBw&usg=AFQjCNFBHvLheqgo4Apb4qAdsneBRVUf1w|format=pdf}}</ref> In [[<U+0130>stanbul]] alone, there are 269,388 people from Kars.<ref>http://www.sabah.com.tr/Yasam/2014/01/29/istanbulun-nufus-bilgileri-aciklandi</ref><ref>http://medya.zaman.com.tr/2008/07/20/istanbul2.jpg</ref>

According to Nicole Watts, an associate professor of political science at the [[San Francisco State University]], about 20% of the city's population is [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Watts|first=Nicole F.|title=Activists in Office: Kurdish Politics and Protest in Turkey (Studies in Modernity and National Identity)|date=2010|publisher=University of Washington Press|location=Seattle|isbn=978-0-295-99050-7|page=[http://books.google.com/books?id=yXWl40KJfKEC&pg=PA167&dq=Kars+(about+20+percent+Kurdish)&hl=en&sa=X&ei=DY5DU7jKJ4qc2QXYhYCACQ&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Kars%20(about%2020%20percent%20Kurdish)&f=false 167]}}</ref>

